{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1781082491297,"sessionID":"ses_14f37e5c0ffewUVDEfJ2NQ59Gq","part":{"id":"prt_eb0ca09990012wB2ihPu9Lnv0Y","messageID":"msg_eb0c9fe3c001DCEQtjgEUO0QfS","sessionID":"ses_14f37e5c0ffewUVDEfJ2NQ59Gq","snapshot":"4b825dc642cb6eb9a060e54bf8d69288fbee4904","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1781082506623,"sessionID":"ses_14f37e5c0ffewUVDEfJ2NQ59Gq","part":{"id":"prt_eb0ca099d0012QgNHxaLUGSYU8","messageID":"msg_eb0c9fe3c001DCEQtjgEUO0QfS","sessionID":"ses_14f37e5c0ffewUVDEfJ2NQ59Gq","type":"text","text":"There's a `t6_special_names_default` test with empty flags (`[]`). When the agent's binary runs with no flags, oracle GNU `ls` will use its default quoting style (`shell-escape` for non-terminal output). The agent must match this. The instruction does say:\n\n> \"The default quoting style for GNU `ls` is **`shell-escape`** when output is not a terminal in recent coreutils — however, the test environment pins behavior via flags, so implement each named style precisely\"\n\nThis is slightly contradictory — instruction says \"test env pins behavior via flags\" but the actual test runs with no flags. However, the instruction does tell agent what the default is (shell-escape for non-terminal), so the agent CAN infer this. Mild but inferable.\n\nAlso the env vars are set: `LC_ALL=C`, `COLUMNS=80`, `TERM=xterm-256color`. Output is to a pipe (not terminal), so default = `shell-escape`. The instruction documents this. OK.\n\nNow let me check `--show-control-chars`. The instruction says:\n> \"**`--show-control-chars`** turns off the `-q` default substitution.\"\n\nBut that's a misstatement. The actual GNU `ls` behavior of `--show-control-chars` is independent and only matters when output is to terminal where `-q` would be default. With output to a pipe (non-terminal), `-q` is NOT default. So `--show-control-chars` without `-q` would behave like default — and on non-terminal output, that's shell-escape default. This is subtle but the agent has to match. Let me also verify `--show-control-chars` test:\n\nThe test `t6_special_names_show_ctrl` uses `[\"--show-control-chars\"]`. Agent must match GNU ls output exactly. The instruction does name and describe `--show-control-chars` and gives all needed semantics. Probably inferable but tricky.\n\nNow check that long-format combined tests are inferable. Instruction says long format details aren't focus, but they are required. The instruction lists `-l` in the table as a required flag and says \"cases that use it require correct long output\". This puts a substantial implicit burden on the agent — they need full `-l` long format implementation (mode, links, owner, group, size, time, name). The instruction doesn't describe long format in detail at all. The agent must use standard GNU ls long format knowledge.\n\nLong format is a well-known standard. This is borderline OK but agents might think \"long format is out of scope\" given the headline framing. Let me also see if symlinks behavior is in long format:\n\nt6 symlinks tests: `t6_symlinks_escape` `-b`, `t6_symlinks_quote_name` `-Q`, `t6_symlinks_literal` `-N`, `t6_symlinks_qs_c`, `t6_symlinks_qs_shell` — none use `-l`. OK, only `-l*` on special_names. Long format with quoted/escaped names. The arrow `->` for symlinks doesn't apply here since special_names has no symlinks.\n\nFor special_names long format: needs mode, link count, user/group (root since baked), size, time, name (with quoting). That's significant work, but inferrable from \"GNU ls -l\".\n\nLet me also check `oracle.yaml`, `job.yaml` briefly:","time":{"start":1781082491293,"end":1781082506618}}}
