{"type":"text","timestamp":1781082527531,"sessionID":"ses_14f37e5c0ffewUVDEfJ2NQ59Gq","part":{"id":"prt_eb0ca517e001usSIfxmqnuzama","messageID":"msg_eb0ca48430011MjM58dsh3P1H8","sessionID":"ses_14f37e5c0ffewUVDEfJ2NQ59Gq","type":"text","text":"Now check tools_accessible — solve.sh tools check at start:\n\nsolve.sh uses `openssl enc -d`. It doesn't validate openssl is present at start. But openssl is installed in Dockerfile. solve.sh has `set -euo pipefail` so it will fail loudly. OK.\n\nFor the agent path: `cargo build --release` must work. The Dockerfile installs Rust toolchain into `/usr/local/cargo` with `a+rX`. PATH is set system-wide. test.sh build phase explicitly sets `PATH=/usr/local/cargo/bin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin` for the build under `su agent`. So cargo is accessible.\n\nNow check on `/app/workspace/examples/expected/*.txt` — instruction tells agent: \"Example fixtures are in `/app/workspace/examples/`. Test fixtures are in `/app/fixtures/` and test definitions in `/app/tests/`.\" Let me verify these exist:\n\nThe build_tests.py creates `/app/fixtures` and `/app/tests` (informational copies). The Dockerfile then does `chown -R agent:agent /app` after copying authoritative versions into root-only `/tests`. So agent CAN read `/app/fixtures` and `/app/tests`. Good — instruction matches.\n\nBut: `/app/workspace/examples/` has only `README.md` in the source repo. The Dockerfile copies `workspace/` first, then `build_tests.py` runs `create_examples()` which copies `basic/` fixture and a few `expected/*.txt` into `/app/workspace/examples/`. Good — instruction matches.\n\nNow for fairness summary:\n\n- **instruction_verifier_sync**: Verifier scores quoting tests + some `-l` long-format combos. Instruction documents all flags including `-l`. Some tests use no flags (default behavior) — instruction documents default as `shell-escape`. Overall reasonably synced, though `-l` long format requires more implementation than the \"quoting focus\" framing suggests.\n- **definitions_documented**: All flags and quoting styles documented in instruction.md with semantics. `-l` long format relies on standard GNU ls knowledge — borderline.\n- **tools_accessible**: Rust toolchain accessible to agent (system-wide install with a+rX). All workspace paths agent expects exist. solve.sh doesn't explicitly validate tool versions but it's a simple decrypt+copy; openssl is available.\n- **oracle_exists**: solve.sh exists and non-empty (decrypts baked oracle binary).\n- **hidden_test_fairness**: Hidden tests run combos of documented flags on standard fixtures (basic/mixed/symlinks/special_names). The instruction explicitly says evaluation uses \"a fixture of filenames containing spaces, single/double quotes, tabs, backslashes, embedded control characters, and a newline, plus a few ordinary fixtures\". Tests are structural variants of documented behavior.\n\nLet me also note: instruction mentions \"`/app/tests/`\" — but agent should be told these are informational only (the authoritative versions are root-only). Let me check what's actually in `/app/tests`:\n\nbuild_tests.py writes test definitions to `/app/tests` then Dockerfile copies them to `/tests` (root) and leaves `/app/tests` for agent. So agent CAN see the test JSON definitions. They show flags + fixture names. Agent can study them but cannot tamper with the authoritative copy. That's fine for fairness — actually helps the agent know what's tested. Good.","time":{"start":1781082509694,"end":1781082527526}}}
